segments.text: entrevista con la señorita, ¿cómo se llama?
Gabriela Gámez.
Gabriela Gámez.
¿Y dónde nació usted?
Yo nací en, era como, aquí dicen un rancho muy grande, y allá le nombran Hacienda de México.
Yo nací en la Hacienda de Dolores.
¿En qué estado?
Tamaulipas.
Sí.
Estado de Tamaulipas.
y me bautizaron en Padilla.
Bueno, díganme más sobre esta hacienda de Dolores.
Bueno, yo nací allí.
Yo nomás nací allí en la hacienda de Dolores porque allí trabajaba mi padre y recibían ellos.
Era, pues, como verigrace aquí un rancho que hay muchos
There were a lot of people to work with.
But the little town where they went was called Padilla, Tamaulipas.
And now it's a big town.
The town is called what?
Padilla, Tamaulipas.
And it was close to what?
Ciudad Victoria.
It's the capital of Padilla and the neighboring towns, like here.
Like Austin and all these towns in the capital of Texas.
The capital of Tamaulipas.
And was the Delores farm very big?
My father told me that it was.
There were many workers.
And what kind of crops did they have?
They were all farmers, workers.
seeders of corn, because it was what they sowed in Mexico.
Corn, beans, cane to make the sweet, the sweet.
My father worked in that, it was called the molienda, where they ground all the cane to get the sweetness out of the cane, to make the sweet and make the sweet.
As they make molasses here, there is one, and there they made the sweet, they made it and then they
Yes, he is a work specialist.
And your mother too?
No, my mother didn't work.
My mother only worked at home.
My mother would look after us, make my father's food, wash, iron.
How many children were there?
When we were there, there were only three of us.
Me, my older sister who lives in Corpus, Mrs. Martinez, and me.
and my brother, who died four years ago.
And these other three were born here in the United States.
Juan, my brother, Maria, my brother, and Manuel, my brother, the youngest in the family.
I lived here in the colony.
And in this farm, how many years did you have?
Well, when we moved here,
Where my father went, it was called the Rosario Farm.
Yes.
Also a farm with a lot of agriculture.
Yes.
Well, that's where my father spent a lot of time, and that's where my father moved here, to the United States.
What year?
August 14, 1916.
He moved here, to the United States.
And since then, he has never returned to Mexico.
No?
No.
Why not?
Well...
Later on, he needed a lot of permission.
He didn't know how to read, my father, but he was a very correct man with all people.
He didn't want to say that he wanted to violate the law of the United States.
That's why he never went back to Mexico.
He said that his mother and sisters had already finished.
And if I have my family here, why would I go?
That's why she was never there for me.
And you, no?
No, I went to see Matamoros.
I only know Matamoros.
Yes.
Because I had some relatives, an aunt.
No, not her, not her daughters.
And they came with us when my father died.
After my father died, at the age of two, my aunt, my father's little sister, died.
And my brother, Manuel.
I had vacations, so they wanted us to go.
And we went so that I could stay there for a few weeks, so that I wouldn't forget a little.
Because my parents both died the same week.
And your family never wants to live in Mexico again?
Well, no, because they are from here, my brothers.
Oh, yes, your brothers are from here.
And my parents died.
I'm Mexican, but what am I going to do there?
I have my siblings.
I have my papers.
I have my passport.
My parents fixed my passport.
Jose fixed his, because he lost his passport.
He went to immigration.
They asked him why he didn't give me his passport.
He said, I'm going to tell you the truth.
He said, I don't know how to read or write.
You didn't?
No.
You didn't go to school?
No, because when we were little, we lived in a ranch called Casamorada.
It was close to Canara, but there were seven days to come on foot.
My father said it was very hard for us to come on foot, except for the two of us, me and my sister.
And this one was here, right?
Yes.
How old were you when you left Mexico?
I was six, I think.
I was born in 1910 and we passed on in 1916.
I was about six years old, but I was five and a half years old.
And your older sister went to school in Mexico?
No.
Are there schools in this estate?
Yes, there were, but my parents came here.
Yes.
No, it wasn't school yet, because in Mexico, my mother and I, some of them were older, others younger, like that.
Yes.
That's why we didn't have a school.
None of my brothers had a school.
No?
No.
Your brothers, no?
No.
Those who were born here?
No, because they were the ones who lived in Calale.
In the ranch.
In the ranch.
And it was very far.
The school was here, in Calale.
How many miles is the school?
Well, there was...
I think there's about six or seven miles from Calale to that ranch.
We had to walk.
And there were no buses or anything?
No, there were before.
I was 23, 24.
23, yes.
There was no... That's why many people said, well, now the children don't go to school.
Because they don't want to, because there are voices for them to go, right?
Yes.
So, no.
My father said, well, I don't send my girls to school because they are very far away.
They are girls, women.
Well, there were my boys, well, two, who were my brother and sister.
The other one was younger, he was in high school, I think, Juan.
But then they treated them very badly, the other boys from school, they treated them very badly.
And my dad said, well, one day they're going to hit them, they're going to break their foot or something.
And it's very far, so when I go, I'm going to bring them.
And he lived working, because all the time he was a farmer, my dad.
Yes.
He worked all the time at the ranch as a farmer.
But is this work in the farm more important or not?
In Mexico, yes.
Well, it was their work.
There were a lot of workers, my mother said.
The work was purely to make canals, you know?
Yes.
To water the work.
Yes.
With pure shovel.
Yes.
Do you know what a shovel is?
To build.
There wasn't like here, where they did it with machines and everything.
Yes.
In those years that my father lived, he was young, he only had my sister and me.
We were three in the family.
Yes.
We were six in the family.
Well, for what reason did you come here to the United States?
Well, they came when, you remember, here also in some
I don't know, years ago.
A lot of people also went to Mexico because there was going to be a lot of war here in the United States, right?
Yes.
Well, then, in Mexico there was also a lot of war and a lot of people came here because the war was very hard there.
Tell me about this war.
Well, I don't know, but my mom says that that's why they came from there, from where they lived, from where they lived.
Yes.
Because there was a lot of war.
Like there is now in Vietnam.
So many people who run from other towns to mountains, to mountains, to hide.
And in Mexico, I think they were born like that too.
And a lot of people came because they were not going to kill their children.
They were civilians, they were not soldiers in the war.
And many soldiers came and entered a town.
Yes.
And for that reason, many people, many families came to see my mother.
Well, I don't know, my mother talked to us and my father didn't.
Yes, yes.
Well, it was very dangerous.
Well, I think so.
And many, many people were killed.
Who knows, I think, I don't know.
My mother says that's why they came here.
First they went to Hacienda del Rosario, on the other side of the river.
Hacienda del Rosario, it's closer to the river.
Yes, it's close to Matamoros, over there.
Yes.
From Matamoros to here.
And less war there?
No, no, no, no.
In this hacienda, Rosario.
Ah, no, no.
There was no peaceful like here.
Ah, it was more peaceful in these years.
Yes.
But Hacienda de Dolores was not peaceful.
Well, no, because they came suddenly like in Vietnam, so peaceful, and suddenly they began to fight, you know?
Yes.
The war.
Well, that's how it was in Mexico in those years.
Yes.
That's why many people came here.
Many families.
They came from this town to here.
Other towns also came.
Yes.
And then my mother and I stayed at the Rosario farm.
And then my father went to work here.
And until I say that it was very hard for her to be there with us and him here.
Maybe he tried to find a way to get by.
And then they didn't pay anything, just a nickel and they passed.
Here?
Yes.
Ah, just a nickel?
Para pasar entonces.
Ah, para pasar.
Sí, para pasar el río, you know.
Sí.
Como ahora usted va para México, pues pasa por el puente.
Pero la chequean el pasaporte, los papeles y todo.
Entonces, no, nomás le pagaba un nikle o un daimel por, según la familia que tuviera, y se la pasaba.
Ah, ¿en qué pueblo pasaba?
En, yo creo que es en Toluca, Toluca.
On the side of Mercedes.
Toluca, Tamaulipas?
No, Toluca, Texas.
Toluca, Texas?
Ah, yes.
I think it's in the middle of Mercedes and Tona.
I don't know.
I don't know.
I don't know those towns.
I don't know much.
Because when I was older, we came to Roestán with an aunt of mine.
With my aunt, a sister of my father.
And I came with her.
With her?
With your aunt?
Yes.
And another little sister, the one who didn't die.
A little sister who was born in the Rosary and my mom brought her a baby when she came.
But she died here when she was 12 years old.
Oh, how sad.
Yes, because, how do you say it?
We were working, working, and she was 12 years old.
In that, we went like this, and I said, Papa, go for a walk, so we can go back to work.
And they put on some long linen dresses for the pizca.
Yes.
Very curious.
And she was putting them on, and a cart was coming.
So the auntie said, come on, little girl, get out of the cart.
And she got very scared.
She got very scared.
Making me be scared, you know?
Very nervous.
Yes.
Y ella dijo el doctor, cuando mi papá la llevó con el doctor, mi mamá, que ella estaba, ¿cómo?
Cuando es girl at 20 years old is making, para ser una girl, you know?
Paseo a mujer.
Sí, bueno.
Ella estaba, el doctor dijo que ella estaba para hacerse así, una señorita.
Sí.
Y ella se asustó mucho y todo su blood se stopped, you know?
Se stopped, you know, coming in.
Blood?
Uh-huh.
Her blood didn't go down anymore.
And that's why she died very soon.
How sad.
Yes.
Her mother died three weeks later.
And she was very sad.
She didn't talk and she didn't feel bad.
No tenía fiebre, no tenía nada.
No tuviste.
No tuviste.
Y no.
Stop.
Porque dijo el doctor que se veía todas las... Estas big venas, you know?
Estas.
Sí.
Se... Stop.
No caminaron con el big susto.
Y ella estaba para hacerse una picro, una señorita.
Sí.
Se stop.
Con el big susto del carro.
Porque venía el hombro muy grueso y ella venía así.
She didn't say anything, no talk, no nothing.
She was very scared and then she started talking, but she said she was very scared.
Are there doctors to assist her?
Yes, doctors cured her and everything, but all the doctors said it was the same.
Because she was very young, she was 12 years old, 13.
She was going to get a surgery.
a lady, and she said, that's very bad, that's a very bad scare, when they are going to start to do a bichloro, that's a very bad scare.
And she died in this ranch?
No, she died here by the Hawaii Nile, but then there was no Hawaii Nile, there was a little ranch, and there we lived with
A lady who was a teacher, her name was Maria McEnbride.
My father used to work with her.
We lived there and she got sick.
She died.
Yes.
She had many years of death.
Yes.
She was very young when she died.
I was the only one left.
My older sister, I have an older sister in the family, she has bodies.
She lives in bodies.
And then...
Me and my brother, who died.
And then Juan.
This is the one from here, from the United States, who was born.
Juan and Maria and Manuel.
Two men and a woman from here.
And from Mexico, two men, no, two women and a man.
And a man, yes.
There were six families.
Well, and what kind of work did your brother Juan have?
Juan Gomez Jr., the one who lived here?
Or the big one?
The one who died?
Yes.
All his life, from the age of 17, he started working in a junkyard.
Do you know what a junkyard is?
Where they make cars and... Oh, a place...
Yes, to make cars, to cut cars.
A person comes and wants a part of a car, for example, and they cut it.
That's what he worked on.
From the age of 17, he started working.
Yes.
Until he died.
After his work, on Saturday, he arrived at his work and told his wife.
He said, I'm going to take a bath, and there's your clothes.
He took his bath, dressed, and said,
I said, first of all, I'm going to pay the bills for the electricity bill.
And he said, you know what you do, right?
I said, yes.
He said, I'll be back in a little while.
And he left.
And when he came back, he didn't come back.
Because when he came back, a friend who worked together in the same place, he said, where are you going?
Gámez.
He said, I'm going to pay my bills.
He said, I'm going there too.
I said, come, I have a ride.
He said, well.
They went and paid the bills, and on the way back, a big truck, a garbage truck.
And he killed himself.
He left... With the garbage truck?
The big truck hit them on their furniture.
Two were killed, my brother and another.
Another man, and the driver had like...
Six months, like four months in the hospital, because he just broke down from here.
But my brother died later.
The other man came to the hospital, he lasted 15 minutes, alive.
My brother was taken out of the hospital.
Very sad.
Yes, very sad.
And he left the family.
11 children.
He had 11 children.
And his wife, what is possible for her with so many children?
Yes, but... She had the oldest, he was already in Vietnam in the war.
The oldest.
The oldest.
Yes.
He was 18 years old and he was in Vietnam.
Is he in Vietnam now?
No, they already completed it.
Ah, yes.
They completed it.
And does he help his mother with us?
Well, yes, the children are all grown up and almost all of them are married.
He only has two children left in the house and two children.
The others are all married, but he is the only one left.
And did she have a job?
No, she never worked.
Never?
She was at home with the children and my brother.
He said he didn't need to go to work because he worked.
Yes.
No, you need to go to work.
I work for you, for my children.
Yes.
All the time, I work, I work, all the time.
Because my father didn't teach them, he said, no, I didn't teach my children school, but I taught them to work and to respect people.
Yes.
Especially a great man of age, to respect him.
Yes.
Because when my father and mother died, they were already married.
They had a family.
Not a big one, but a small one.
And they didn't smoke in front of my father.
No?
No.
They did smoke.
He knew they smoked, but in front of him, when they sat down to talk, and many people, now many children, their father was sitting and drinking, saying, they were drinking beer, right?
Yes.
They didn't smoke in front of him, because they respected his father.

My father, well, he didn't teach them how to smoke, but he taught them how to behave well with older people, and he would say, in front of an older person, don't smoke, don't ask for firewood to light a cigarette, or anything like that.
If they wanted to smoke,
Ustedes carguen sus mechas o vayan a buscar lumbre en otra parte.
Pero nunca le pidan a un señor grande de edad, a una persona más grande que ustedes.
Porque no es correcto.
Es falta de educación.
Sí.
Y su papá estaba muy correcto.
Sí.
De todos.
Sí.
En trabajo, en dirigir sus hijos.
Cuando ya se casaron, les dijo, el que se casó primero fue Juan.
Después del más chiquito, que fue Meme.
Dijo, usted ya se le acabó de andar en la calle a las 11.
Ya para las 8 puede ir a tomarse una cerveza con sus amigos, a platicar un ratito.
No se le quita nada, pero como Dios manda y correctamente.
Pero ya para las 9 tiene que estar en su casa, porque su obligación aquí la tiene.
You have your wife, you have your children.
You are no longer on the street.
The street is for those who have not been married.
You can talk to your friends.
You can talk to your friends, but in other places you shouldn't do that.
The street is over for you.
Yes.
And they were like that.
They were like, as my father would say, they were like that.
Well, where did your father come from?
My father was from
He was born in Sotolamarina.
Sotolamarina.
Yes, I know.
She was born there and she got baptized.
But he got married here in Hacienda Dolores in Tamaulipas.
Here in Padilla with my mother.
Your mother was from Hacienda?
My mother was a native of Tamaulipas.
She was born in Padilla and she got married with my father.
My father was born in Sotolamarina.
When my grandmother became a widow because her father died, my father came to Padilla when he was 12 years old with his mother and other sisters.
Y ahí se hizo hombre.
Ahí se enseñó a trabajar.
Y ahí se hizo hombre él.
Y ahí se casó con mi mamá.
Sí.
Con mi mamá.
¿Cómo se llama su papá?
Juan Gámez.
Juan Cruz Gámez.
Juan Gámez de la Cruz.
Juan Gámez.
No Gómez.
Gámez.
Gámez.
Diferente.
Sí.
Hay Gómez y nosotros hemos Gámez.
Gámez.
Gámez.
Es un nombre y poco diferente.
Sí.
Gámez.
Gámez.
Como esto.
Gámez.
Juan Gámez, the lord of the cross.
He was born on the 3rd of May, the day of the Holy Cross.
He is the one who has the name of the Cross.
In what year was your father born?
I don't know.
I do know, but I don't remember.
When they died, there are the names on the stone.
The year they were born.
The year they died.
They now have...
They completed 16 years of death.
Sixteen.
Since he died?
Since he died.
Yes.
That's where they died, where I live.
In San Juan Addition, in the colony.
That's where they died.
In San Juan?
Addition, here.
The colony of Corpus Christi?
Yes, here, one of mine from here.
Ah, yes.
And when he was your age, what kind of work did your father have?
Well, he worked here with this lady.
Mr. Hugh Weiss worked here for a long time.
Yes.
We lived here.
From here we came back to the suburb, to the colony we lived in.
Yes.
I worked with the gentlemen.
Well, just as I worked with the gentlemen, I made the pipes and worked, because before I had no job, I worked as a laborer.
What year did you come here?
In 1900, here with this ranch?
Yes.
We came in November of 1938.
And how old were you?
About 18 or 19 years old.
I worked with them for 20 years.
And then they said they were going on vacation.
They left.
And then I went to my house.
I worked from 1938 to 1958.
Yes.
And then I went.
And then I worked with other Americans in bodies.
Yes.
And from there I worked for a long time with another lady, but then she got married.
She was a widow and she got married.
And then I came and she got married.
One day Rusty Blount told me that he was going to work with him one day.
He said he didn't have a job.
I said no, because the boss got married.
She told Carola that I wasn't working.
Mejor hablar.
Yo tengo un año de estar trabajando para atrás.
¿Y para cuantos años estaba aquí ahora?
Tengo un año ahora.
Nueve años aquí.
No, un año.
Ahorita para atrás, de vuelta, tengo un año.
Ah, de vuelta, un año.
Pero trabajé...
Twenty years with them.
In these years, they married.
Yes.
Twenty years.
I was more middle-aged, more young.
Yes.
And you never married?
No.
No?
Why not?
Well, I don't know, because I was... My brothers got married.
My brother, Juan, got married first.
And then Pedro, my brother, who died.
Yes.
He was the oldest, but he got married later.
And then...
My sister, Mariela, also lives in Alma, Colombia.
And I stayed because I always... How do you say it?
I was always very... very... How do you say it?
Very content with my father and mother.
Yes, yes.
Because I worked all the time.
I used to work all the time and the lady used to pay me and give me my check or money.
I used to take it to my dad.
Yes.
I used to bring it to my dad.
My dad used to say, that's my boy who keeps us.
Yes.
When he got married, he used to say, that's my boy who keeps us because the boys got married.
And when I don't work, he keeps us.
Yes.
And that's why I never got married.
Because, I don't know, I always wanted to be with my mom.
with my mom.
Yes, it's a lot of responsibility to your parents.
And I was always there for them.
And then they died and I was left alone.
Yes.
And then I felt very sad because my mom died, my dad first, and then my mom.
I stayed with an aunt, excuse me, alone.
And then she died.
Yes.
Two years after my mother and father died, he died.
Yes.
And then I was left alone.
Then my younger brother, who lived here, moved there too.
Then I had a house and sold it.
I made that little one where I live.
Yes.
I live alone, but as an example,
Well, this house is my brother Juan's house.
I have respect for him.
I know my sister lives there.
I live in my little house.
Does your brother live here too?
Yes, he lives in San Juan.
The other one lived there, but he moved there.
We all lived there when my father died.
Is San Juan very close?
One is mine here.
One is mine here.
Ah, it's very close.
Yes.
And your family was here?
Yes.
When my father died and my mother, they were all there.
Not together, but everyone in their house.
Yes.
Well, tell me about your trip to Hacienda de Dolores.
to this other hacienda, the trip?
I don't know because I don't remember.
But what did your mother say about these things?
No, my mother says that they came from there.
It was my father because he came first to this hacienda.
And he wrote to her and sent her money for food for us.
So he wrote to her and told her to get ready because he was going to go
I asked him how many days he was going.
He said, are you ready?
I said, are the girls ready?
Are you ready?
Well, you can bring clothes for them and for you.
Yes.
And then my father went and brought her there.
Yes.
To the Hacienda de Dolores.
Yes.
And his families stayed there.
Yes.
So my mother had her mother and my grandmother.
Yes.
But my father's mother had already passed away.
Yes.
In what way?
In Bahia?
I don't remember.
I don't know.
They didn't tell me.
I think I was in Guayin because they were in Guayin.
Guayin.
What is a Guayin?
With mules.
Oh, with mules!
But they are called Guayines.
Guayines, with mules.
And is it a very long trip?
I don't know.
I think it is because it is a little far.
From Tamaulipas to...
It's a little far.
Yes.
But now, by car, it's not very far.
I think it's less than a day away.
Yes, but in Guayí, it's quite far.
I don't know where it is, but maybe in Guayí, because it was what I saw before.
There were no cars.
No, not these days.
Is there enough to eat on this trip?
Yes, I think so, my father had it.
Well, he worked.
Yes.
And then he sowed, he had, well, how do you say, half, they gave me.
Well, the boss gave him certain acres of land, my father cultivated them.
Ajá.
They sowed what they had to sow, what they picked up from the harvest, half for him and half for the boss.
Yes, I understand.
And what kind of houses did you have?
Well, my mom used to say they were adobe houses.
Adobe?
Yes, adobe houses.
My mom made some pictures like this, a little bigger.
Yes.
They used to beat the cement here, you know?
Yes.
But over there they beat it with dirt, with water.
They made them and then they made the house out of pure adobe.
And the floor was made of adobe.
Yes.
And the roof was made of straw, my mom says.
Yes.
Straw is like...
There's a very big roof, right?
Yes.
And the...
They put the ceilings, but the houses don't get wet.
First they put only sticks like this.
Yes.
And you see how they make houses over there in the overseas, the Japanese and all that.
Yes, and also in Mexico.
Well, and they put only sticks like this, and then there they put only zakate, but well composed, well settled.
Yes.
And the houses don't get wet.
They all had good houses, big ones for families.
In this farm, for all the families, there were good houses?
Yes, good houses.
And the owner paid a lot?
Yes, he paid them.
I don't know how much he would earn in Mexico, I don't know, because then they paid a little.
But as it was the farm, and he was a farmer, well, that was fine.
For example, from what they sowed, they took out half, half for the landowner and half for the miller, for the worker.
And the corn, my mother says that they soaked it in the mafrota, then they took it out and put it in bags, in bags.
And then they came to buy it, they sold it, because it was pure money they had, and beans and all that.
Life was good in the days before the war.
Yes.
And then when we were here in Kuala Lumpur, we never... Well, they didn't pay much, so my father would plant a little cotton and all that.
But my father was always a man who planted.
Mi mamá tenía muchas gallinas.
¿Sí?
Muchas gallinas.
¿Aquí en qué?
Sí, en Calale, en el rancho.
En el otro rancho.
En el rancho donde nació mi hermanito de chico.
¿Cómo se llama este rancho?
Le decían Casa Morada.
